04696nam a22006615i 9781477317419DE-B159720211129102213.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||211129t20212019txu    fo  d z      eng d  a2017058303  a97814773174197 a10.7560/3173962doi  a(DE-B1597)587383  a(OCoLC)1269268325  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  atxucUS-TX00aF2520.1.C32bM55 2019 7aSOC0000002bisacsh04a581.6/309812231 aMiller, Theresa L., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aPlant Kin :bA Multispecies Ethnography in Indigenous Brazil /cTheresa L. Miller. 1aAustin : bUniversity of Texas Press, c[2021] 4c©2019  a1 online resource (328 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tCONTENTS -- tLIST OF ILLUSTRATIONS -- tIntroduction Toward a Sensory Ethnobotany in the Anthropocene -- tChapter One Tracing Indigenous Landscape Aesthetics in the Changing Cerrado -- tChapter Two Loving Gardens: Human–Environment Engagements in Past and Present -- tChapter Three Educating Affection Becoming Gardener Parents -- tChapter Four Naming Plant Children Ethnobotanical Classification as Childcare -- tChapter Five Becoming a Shaman with Plants Friendship, Seduction, and Mediating Danger -- tConclusion Exploring Futures for People and Plants in the Twenty-First Century -- tEPILOGUE -- tACKNOWLEDGMENTS -- tAPPENDIX A Living Lists of Canela Cultivated Crops -- tAPPENDIX B Living Lists of Canela Native Plants in Savannah, Chapada, and Riverbank -- tAPPENDIX C Star-Woman (Caxêtikwỳj) Mythic Story -- tNOTES -- tREFERENCES -- tINDEX0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThe Indigenous Canela inhabit a vibrant multispecies community of nearly 3,000 people and over 300 types of cultivated and wild plants living together in Maranhão State in the Brazilian Cerrado (savannah), a biome threatened with deforestation and climate change. In the face of these environmental threats, Canela women and men work to maintain riverbank and forest gardens and care for their growing crops, whom they consider to be, literally, children. This nurturing, loving relationship between people and plants—which offers a thought-provoking model for supporting multispecies survival and well-being throughout the world—is the focus of Plant Kin. Theresa L. Miller shows how kinship develops between Canela people and plants through intimate, multi-sensory, and embodied relationships. Using an approach she calls “sensory ethnobotany,” Miller explores the Canela bio-sociocultural life-world, including Canela landscape aesthetics, ethnobotanical classification, mythical storytelling, historical and modern-day gardening practices, transmission of ecological knowledge through an education of affection for plant kin, shamanic engagements with plant friends and lovers, and myriad other human-nonhuman experiences. This multispecies ethnography reveals the transformations of Canela human-environment and human-plant engagements over the past two centuries and envisions possible futures for this Indigenous multispecies community as it reckons with the rapid environmental and climatic changes facing the Brazilian Cerrado as the Anthropocene epoch unfolds.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Nov 2021) 0aCanella IndiansxEthnobotany. 0aCerrado ecologyzBrazil. 0aHuman-plant relationshipszBrazil. 0aSustainable livingzBrazil. 0aTraditional ecological knowledgezBrazil. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / General.2bisacsh40uhttps://doi.org/10.7560/31739640uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781477317419423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781477317419/original  aEBA_CL_SN  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_SN  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE 